<DOC><DOCNO> AP900623-0021 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-90 0233EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-Names     06-23 0619</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Names,0648</SECOND><HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD><HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD><DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Former racing champ and auto designer CarrollShelby left a Los Angeles hospital in high spirits after a hearttransplant.   Shelby, 67, was released Friday from Cedars-Sinai MedicalCenter, where he had surgery June 8.   ``Everything is fine. It couldn't have gone better,'' hospitalspokesman Ron Wise said.   Wise attributed Shelby's excellent spirits to his speedyrecovery.   ``He acted as if it was no more than a tooth extraction,'' Wisesaid.   Shelby lives on a ranch in Pittsburg, Texas, about 120 milesnortheast of Dallas. He was a three-time U.S. sports car driver ofthe year and in the 1960s designed the Cobra muscle car, the firstaffordable performance car at $6,000.   Shelby had been suffering from congestive heart failure forabout a year prior to the transplant.</TEXT><DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Gloria Estefan, recovering from a broken back,wielded a giant bottle of champagne as she christened a cruise ship.   Ms. Estefan, the singer for Miami Sound Machine, had words ofsupport Friday for another Miami-based act _ 2 Live Crew. Thepopular rap band should not be censored, she said. A federal judgein Florida this month deemed the group's album ``As Nasty As TheyWanna Be'' obscene.   ``To an artist and from the artist's standpoint I feel that weneed to have freedom to be able to express ourselves,'' Ms. Estefansaid.   Ms. Estefan, injured when her tour bus was hit by a truck inMarch, says her recovery is progressing and she is passing time bywriting new songs. But she said it will be some time before shereturns to the stage.   ``I'm at the writing stage now,'' she said.   Ms. Estefan christened the $200 million cruise ship NordicEmpress, operated by Royal Caribbean Cruises Ltd. It took her twoattempts to get the bottle of bubbly to shatter.   At Ms. Estefan's request, Royal Caribbean will donate $25,000 tothe Children's Home Society, which assists abused children.</TEXT><DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Country music star Clint Black isdriving a 1987 Porsche Targa thanks to an idle promise two yearsago from his record producer.   ``I told Clint, `Kid, you get me a gold record and you can havemy Porsche,''' producer James Stroud said.   Black's debut album, ``Killin' Time,'' has sold 1.6 millioncopies. An album must sell 500,000 copies to go gold.   Stroud turned over the flashy red set of wheels this week.   ``I was able to hold off when he went gold, but when he wentplatinum (1 million copies), I pretty much had to give it up,''Stroud said.</TEXT><DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Joan Mondale, wife of former Vice PresidentWalter Mondale, made her orchestra debut as a narrator with theMinnesota Sinfonia.   Mondale, who lives in Minneapolis with her husband, narrated aperformance Friday of ``The Emperor's New Clothes'' and was set fora second performance Sunday.   ``I've always thought working with an orchestra would be theneatest thing in the world,'' she said.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   First lady Barbara Bush praised a new nurseryfor babies handicapped by crack and AIDS.   Mrs. Bush on Friday dedicated Variety House for Children, openedin New York about a month ago by the Association to BenefitChildren.   ``So many kids can accomplish what they set out to do if theyhave the love and care they need and that's what places likeVariety House are for,'' Mrs. Bush said.   The nursery will provide a transitional home for up to sixbabies until foster parents can be found. It also will eventuallyinclude a day care center for up to 12 children infected with theHIV virus.</TEXT></DOC>